<title>BCM_GETLINE</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p><font color="#000000" size="4"><strong>BCM_GETLINE</strong></font></p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="3" width="100%">
    <tr>
        <td width="100%" bgcolor="#E6E6E6"><pre>BCM_GETLINE
	wParam = ( WPARAM )( int )nLineNum;
	lParam = ( LPARAM )( LPTSTR )lpszBuffer;</pre>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

<p>Retrieves the line currently under the caret or a specific line.</p>

<ul>
    <li>Returns one of the following:</li>
    <ul type="disc">
    	<li>Zero for failure.</li>
	<li>A global memory handle when the message has
	allocated the memory for you.</li>
	<li>A pointer to the input buffer.</li>
    </ul>
</ul>

<dl>
    <dt><em>nLineNum</em></dt>
    <dd>The number of the line you want to get or -1 in which case
    the line on which the caret is located will be copied.
    </dd>
    <dt><em>lpszBuffer</em></dt>
    <dd>This can be a pointer to a buffer large enough to
	hold the text. Use the <a href="getlinelength.htm">BCM_GETLINELENGTH</a> message
	to determine the size necessary to store the text.
	<p>If this is zero the routine will allocate the
	necessary memory for you and return it to you as a
	global memory handle. You are responsible for
	dealocating the handle when you are done with it.</p>
</dd>
</dl>

</body>
</html>